Varsity Boys
Riece Rivera- 12th
Grant Springer- 13th
Jack Lancaster- 16th

Varsity Girs
MaKenzie Long- 18th

Middle School Boys
Colten Pilakowski- 1st
Ike Cronin- 3rd

Middle School Girls
Aiden Hand- 6th

Great job Badgers!

post_text:
Please read the following guidelines set forth by the North Central Health Department. If you are showing any of the symptoms on this chart please go visit your health care provider. If they test you for COVID-19, you and every person in the household are required to quarantine.

There are 4 points listed that explain when a child can return to school. If your child meets any one of these criteria they may return to school.

Valentine Community Schools is committed to keeping our doors open and teaching students face to face. Please be honest with your symptoms and the health care provider's directions so we can do what's best for our students and community.

post_text: To kick things off this year, Valentine‚Äôs local FBLA chapter had its organizational meeting at the trailhead on Tuesday the 18th of August. These Future Business leaders ate pizza and snacks while our officer team mapped out the activities for this upcoming school year. Thank you to everyone who helped out and who came to see what this organization is all about. We are excited to see what this group will accomplish and the new skills they will grow and develop as we move forward into this difficult time. If you are a student at VHS and want to join the team, there is still time. We are accepting new members for one more week...September 4th is our registration goal! Check out the posters all around the high school for more details. #NE1kFBLA @NebraskaFBLA

post_text:
We know the ACT has been on your mind and likely the minds of your students. The current plan is this:

1. All seniors (Class of 2021) will take the ACT in September to make up for the test they missed this past March. The exact date is still being determined, but it will be on a school day at no cost to you. The school also completes all student registrations on their behalf for THIS TEST ONLY.
2. Students will also be able to take the test on the following Saturdays throughout the school year: September 12, October 24, December 12, February 6, and April 17.
3. Registration for the September 12 test date opened on July 27 and closes on August 14. Mark your calendars! Students can still register August 15-August 28 but would be required to pay a $30 late fee. Registration must be completed at act.org.
4. ACT also made the following decision: "The launch of Section Retesting and Online Testing have been postponed until 2021. Only paper and pencil full tests will be offered at sites this fall."

Questions? Contact Mrs. Kilmer at rkilmer@vcsbadger.net
text:
We know the ACT has been on your mind and likely the minds of your students. The current plan is this:

1. All seniors (Class of 2021) will take the ACT in September to make up for the test they missed this past March. The exact date is still being determined, but it will be on a school day at no cost to you. The school also completes all student registrations on their behalf for THIS TEST ONLY.
2. Students will also be able to take the test on the following Saturdays throughout the school year: September 12, October 24, December 12, February 6, and April 17.
3. Registration for the September 12 test date opened on July 27 and closes on August 14. Mark your calendars! Students can still register August 15-August 28 but would be required to pay a $30 late fee. Registration must be completed at act.org.
4. ACT also made the following decision: "The launch of Section Retesting and Online Testing have been postponed until 2021. Only paper and pencil full tests will be offered at sites this fall."

Questions? Contact Mrs. Kilmer at rkilmer@vcsbadger.net

post_text:
Hello Valentine Community Schools parents, my name is Mike Halley and I'm excited to be your new superintendent of schools! We are working on developing a return to school program for students this fall, and would really like to have input from all of you! We are working with the Nebraska Association of School Boards (NASB), to conduct a survey of all parents in the district, and get some valuable feedback as we develop our plans. The deadline for completing this survey is midnight, July 16, 2020. Please take a few minutes to complete this survey and help us with our fall planning. I look forward to working with all of you to provide a great education for your students!
Thank you,

Mike Halley
Superintendent
Valentine Community Schools

All VCS teachers and administrators are doing some professional development today and tomorrow. We are tuning into the Future Ready Online Conference. We hope this information will give our faculty and admin information on the next school year and give us more tools to make education more effective in a traditional and digital classroom.

Every year, the incoming sixth grade students get to make a choice about their music class(es). VMS offers band, choir, and study hall. If your student chooses band only, they will have band on Monday, Wednesday, and Friday and study hall on Tuesday and Thursday. If your student chooses choir only, they will have choir on Tuesday and Thursday and study hall on Monday, Wednesday, and Friday. If your student chooses band and choir, they will NOT have a study hall. Please fill out this form to indicate your student's choice.

https://forms.gle/ot6oH6zkGvcJrivF6

post_text: Valentine Community Schools will be doing a book and technology check-in next week. This would include textbooks, library books, laptops or chromebooks, and any other school property. Families with last names starting with A-F will check-in on Monday, May 18; G-M will check in on Tuesday, May 19; and N-Z will check in on Wednesday, May 20. Each day, the buildings will be open 9 am-3 pm. This will be for all three schools, VES, VMS, and VHS; you will check in to each building you have children attending. Two people at a time will be admitted in the building, and that will be it. Practicing social distancing. If there are any issues with the dates, please call the appropriate school.

Last names beginning A-E from 9:00am-10:00 am, F-J 10:00-11:00, K-P 1:00-2:00, R-Y 2:00-3:00. WE will only allow two students at a time. Enter through the East doors. Seniors will also pick up their graduation packets at this time. Students may want to bring some money for any fees/fines they may have.

post_text: Physicals - The NSAA has decided to waive physicals for students who have a physical on file with the school from last year that are entering grades 8, 10, 11 and 12. Incoming 7th graders have to have a physical per state law. Incoming freshmen will have to have a new physical to meet the requirements of the NSAA Catastrophic Insurance coverage. Physicals will need to be scheduled individually through your medical provider after May 1st. Here is a link to the NSAA statement: https://nsaa-static.s3.amazonaws.com/textfile/spmeds/physicals2021.pdf. If you have any questions please contact Mr. Brown at gbrown@vcsbadger.net

post_text:
Starting on April 20, Nebraska Extension educators will be hosting a FREE & LIVE webinar on Mondays and Thursdays at 3 p.m. via Zoom for interested high-school students, teachers, and coaches to join in and learn about sports performance nutrition!

This research-based curriculum will include six interactive lessons, twice a week where students will learn about basic nutrition, nutrient timing, energy balance, building a performance nutrition plate, supplements and MORE!

We look forward to kicking off this program and spreading interest in nutrition and exercise among young athletes!

Topics:
‚Ä¢ Monday, April 20, 3-3:45 p.m. ‚Äî Nutrition 101
‚Ä¢ Thursday, April 23, 3-3:45 p.m. ‚Äî Nutrition 102
‚Ä¢ Monday, April 27, 3-3:45 p.m. ‚Äî Athlete Performance Plate
‚Ä¢ Thursday. April 30, 3-3:45 p.m. ‚Äî Energy Balance and Healthy Living
‚Ä¢ Monday, May 4, 3-3:45 p.m. ‚Äî Timing of Intake
‚Ä¢ Thursday, May 7, 3-3:45 p.m. ‚Äî Supplements

Registration Link: https://forms.gle/coQqt7sMdEM66a3V7

Questions? Contact Extension Educator, Alyssa Havlovic at ahavlovic2@unl.edu

post_text:
Valentine Community Schools will start serving free pre-packaged lunches for children beginning today, March 24th.
The drive-through pickup will take place at Valentine High School and Valentine Middle School from 11:30am ‚Äì 12:00pm on Tuesdays and Thursdays for all children ages 18 and younger. Lunch will be provided in bags with Tuesday‚Äôs bag containing lunch for 2 days and Thursday‚Äôs bag containing lunch for 3 days.
Middle school pickup will be in front of the middle school on Wood Street. High School pickup will be in the parking lot on the south side of the high school.
Guidelines:
>Children must be in the vehicle to receive their bag of food.
>Please do not park and get out of your vehicle.
>Please do not consume meals on site.
>The number of children in the vehicle will determine the number of meals each vehicle gets.
>Meal distribution will begin promptly at 11:30am and end at noon.

post_text: The Valentine Education Association will be offering a $250 scholarship to a local college student. Applicants must be majoring in education and be a junior or senior in college for the 2020-2021 year. Applicants for this scholarship must submit a letter of application stating goals and reasons for majoring in education, as well as a resume with current GPA and two letters of reference. One reference letter should be from a school employee and the other from the community at large. The letters may be included with the application or mailed separately. If you have further questions, email Ronelle Kilmer at rkilmer@vcsbadger.net. Scholarship applications are due May 1, 2020, to Ronelle Kilmer, Valentine High School, 431 N. Green Street, Valentine, Nebraska 69201.
